This place has gone through a few management changes but I think the current ones are it! I did notice a small price increase but I'd say its totally worth it. Their empanadas and pan de bono is always on point and sometimes sell out. Depending on the time they may be in the process of baking more of your favorite goodies, so be patient if you do end up waiting. The staff there is really kind too, make sure to leave a tip!! I've had the chorizo, chicharron, breakfast platters (serves lots of rice), empanadas, buñuelos, pandebono, arepa con queso. It is very small and gets busy here, so if you dine in (max 2-4) you see lots of people come and go.

Had an beef empanada, a pan de bono and a mango juice made with milk. The empanada had good flavor but it tasted like it had been sitting there since the morning, it probably was, I went in the afternoon. The pan de bono was cold, I'm not sure they serve them like that the whole day but it would be better if it was warm or if they offered to heat it up a little. They have maybe the best spicy sauce I have had from a Colombian restaurant. It's a cilantro base but it's got the perfect amount of spice to it. The mango juice was good, it was made from frozen fruit, which I'm fine with, it's better than a bottled or canned beverage. Prices are good and they are very friendly. They menu has more than empanadas and bakery items.
